"Armbruster W., Fischer J.","Improved method of exponential sum fitting of transmissions to describe the absorption of atmospheric gases",1996,"Applied Optics","35","12",,"1931","1941",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0030124937&partnerID=40&md5=07d3c2ef68724f0f1fcf7449830c03ef","Inst. F. Weltraumwissenschaften, Freie Uninversität Berlin, D-14195 Berlin, Germany","Armbruster, W., Inst. F. Weltraumwissenschaften, Freie Uninversität Berlin, D-14195 Berlin, Germany; Fischer, J., Inst. F. Weltraumwissenschaften, Freie Uninversität Berlin, D-14195 Berlin, Germany","For climate modeling and atmospheric research, such as investigations of global climate change, remote sensing of cloud properties, or the missing absorption problem in clouds, it is most important to describe adequately the absorption of radiation by atmospheric gases. An improved method for the exponential sum fitting of transmissions (ESFT) is developed to approximate this absorption accurately. Exponentials are estimated separately for any number of atmospheric-model layers, considering the pressure and temperature dependence of the absorption lines directly. As long as the error of the fit exceeds a limit of tolerance, the number of considered exponential terms is successively increased. The accuracy of the method presented yields a root-mean-square error of less than 0.03% for any atmospheric-model layer, whereas the commonly used one-layer techniques gain errors of up to 3% in the transmission functions for the upper layers. The commonly used ESFT methods consider only one atmospheric layer and introduce the pressure and temperature effects for the other model layers afterward. © 1996 Optical Society of America.","Absorption of atmospheric gases; Exponential sum fitting of transmissions; Radiative transfer; Transmission functions; Transmission in absorbing atmospheres","Absorption; Approximation theory; Computer simulation; Database systems; Gases; Pressure effects; Solar radiation; Thermal effects; Vapors; Water; Atmospheric gas absorption; Error function; Exponential sum fitting of transmissions; Root mean square error; Water vapor; Atmospheric radiation",,,,,,"Stephens, G.L., Tsay, S.-C., On the cloud absorption anomaly (1990) Q. J. R. Meteorol. Soc., 116, pp. 671-704; Scott, N.A., A direct method of computation of the transmission function of an inhomogeneous gaseous medium-I: Description of the method (1974) J. Quant. Spectrosc. Radiat. Transfer, 14, pp. 691-704; Chou, M.D., Monochromatic calculations of atmospheric radiative transfer due to molecular line absorption (1986) J. Geophys. Res., 91, pp. 4047-4055; Hollweg, H.-D., (1990) Strahlungsübertragung in Klaren Atmosphären im IR Mit K-Vertei-lungs- und Linie-für-Linie Modellen, , Ph.D. dissertation Fachbereich Geowissenschaften der Universität Hamburg, Hamburg, Germany; Chou, M.D., Arking, A., An efficient method for computing the absorption of solar radiation by water vapor (1981) J. Atmos. Sci., 38, pp. 798-807; Wiscombe, W.J., Evans, J.W., Exponential sum fitting of radiative transmission functions (1977) J. Comput. Phys., 24, pp. 415-444; Asano, S., Uchiyama, A., Application of an extended ESFT method to calculation of solar heating rates by water vapour absorption (1987) J. Quant. Spectrosc. Radiat. Transfer, 38, pp. 147-158; Raschke, E., Stuke, U., Approximations of band transmission functions by finite sums of exponentials (1973) Beitr. Phys. Atmos., 46, pp. 203-212; Lacis, A.A., Hansen, J.E., A parametrization for the absorption of solar radiation in the Earth's atmosphere (1974) J. Atmos. Sci., 31, pp. 118-132; Liou, K.N., Sasamori, T., On the transfer of solar radiation in aerosol atmospheres (1975) J. Atmos. Sci., 32, pp. 2166-2177; Kerschgens, M., Raschke, E., Reuter, U., The absorption of solar radiation in model atmospheres (1976) Beitr. Phys. Atmos., 49, pp. 81-97; Stephens, G.L., Radiation profiles in extended water clouds (1978) J. Atmos. Sci., 35, pp. 2111-2122; Chou